Please allow me to introduce myself. My name is Andrew Monroe, I am the Rooms Supervisor here at the Hyatt Regency Green Bay. I am reaching out to you today to thank you for taking the time to complete our online survey. It is the feedback from our valued guests such as yourself, which assists us in improving our overall customer service and guest experience. We here at the Hyatt Regency Green Bay take pride in providing both authentic service and clean, comfortable accommodations, however based on your response we have room for improvement. 

Ms. Ryan, I do apologize for apparent miscommunication.  As a globalist you are entitled to free breakfast at any Hyatt Regency property worldwide.  I'm also sorry that our menu is still limited at the current time.  I would enjoy a few more options on the menu as well myself.  We are hoping to expand the menu again in the near future.  If you would be able to please confirm for me the reason you scored your food & beverage experience so low, I'd appreciate it.  Was it solely due to the limited menu available?  Or did you have a bad experience you haven't mentioned yet?  I'd like to know if there's anything else we need to improve upon.  Since you weren't able to utilize your complimentary breakfast benefit, I've taken the liberty of awarding your World of Hyatt account with 5,000 points, the equivalence of a $25 dining credit.

If you have any questions for me or if there is any additional feedback that you wish to provide in regards to how we can better exceed your expectations in the future, please feel free to reach out to me directly. I look forward to hearing back from you at your earliest convenience. Once again, thank you for your time and response.

Sincerely,

Andrew Monroe
Rooms Supervisor
Hyatt Regency Green Bay

I am reaching out to you today to thank you for taking the time to complete our online survey. Mr. Adams, I do apologize for the confusion, but our bathrooms don't actually have individual fans in each room as our ventilation system utilizes what's called a passive ventilation system, basically that means the whole ventilation system is connected and any fans at all are located on the roof of the hotel.  I'm sorry you expected a fan and there wasn't one for you.  I'm glad to know that other than that you had a good stay.

Please allow me to introduce myself. My name is Andrew Monroe, I am the Rooms Supervisor here at the Hyatt Regency Green Bay. Mr. Greenwood, I'm sorry to hear that you did not feel as valued with World of Hyatt as you do with the hotels that you stay with frequently, as we value every one of our guests.  If you look on the World of Hyatt website, new member perks are different based on the specific brand within the Hyatt family you are staying with.  For instance: even as a brand new World of Hyatt member, if you stay at a Hyatt Place hotel, you receive free breakfast.  The longer you are a member of World of Hyatt and stay at our properties more frequently, the perks add up fast. So if you'd elaborate a little on that topic, it would greatly appreciated.

I would like to extend my gratitude for you taking your time to provide your feedback and look forward to hearing back from you at your earliest convenience.  Once again, thank you for your time and your response.

2021-12-29 06:11:47] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Good Morning, Ms. Liggett,

Now I'm sure you're aware of this, but the cost of every single hotel room in Green Bay and the surrounding cities goes up exponentially whenever there is a Green Bay Packers home game.  Also, the closer you get to the date of the game, the higher the rates are for whatever remaining hotel rooms that there are.  Especially if you book in any less than 2 months before the game.  That is when hotel rooms are at the highest that they're ever going to be.  I'm sorry if you were misled to believing that you were receiving any room type other than what you booked, a standard Double Queen Suite, our base level room-type.   If we gave you any indication that you would receive a complimentary upgrade on one of our busiest days of the year, I do sincerely apologize.  

You appear to have misunderstood what I said regarding communicating with the front desk any issues you might have with your room.  Had you expressed your dissatisfaction with your room, we would have gladly found you another room that would hopefully be more to your liking.  In no way does complaining guarantee you'll get an upgrade by any means.  We would have done anything within our ability to get you into a room you are satisfied with so long as we had one available, and we also would have done whatever we deemed necessary to ensure your satisfaction throughout the rest of your stay.  

In regards to Ebru and the welcome letter, I'm sorry if she did in fact not highlight any of the information on your welcome letter, as she is supposed to go over a few major points beyond our mask recommendation.  I appreciate your feedback on your opinion of true customer service.  I will take that into consideration.  I am deeply sorry that you feel the need to stay elsewhere in the future.  I hope that when you are looking at coming to Green Bay for another Packers victory, you'll see the rates other properties charge along with what amenities they offer and compare it to the Hyatt.  If you decide that you would like to go elsewhere, I cannot stop you.  I do ask that you to give us another chance to serve you better in the future.  We'd like the opportunity to "wow" you as we do so many of our guests.  

Happy Holidays and Best Wishes!

Sincerely,

Andrew Monroe
Rooms Supervisor
Hyatt Regency Green Bay
Andrew.Monroe@hyatt.com

column250: Our room smelled musty and was not clean. It was full of dust. We were never told of any of the amenities upon checkin. It sure would’ve been nice to know that the restaurant was open for dinner on Christmas Day night.

column64: ; ; ; ; ; ;Also, there were many empty rooms that night. Why were we put in a room adjoining a room with barking dogs?  We didn’t make a fuss because we are pet owners (whose pets were at home) and it was Christmas but it was annoying.; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;
column65: Also, there were many empty rooms that night. Why were we put in a room adjoining a room with barking dogs?  We didn’t make a fuss because we are pet owners (whose pets were at home) and it was Christmas but it was annoying.
column250:
All of your staff were wearing their masks properly!!!!  Thank you!!!!!  You could sense a smile behind their masks by your staff’s eyes and words. 

Also, we used clorox wipes on all the table and counter tops and light switches when we checked in as we do at all hotels now and you could tell by the lack of dirt on them that someone was cleaning properly. 
One area for improvement is that the breakfast was not explained to us at check-in. 
Overall a very enjoyable stay but rooms could use painting and updates. (Visible water damage in bathroom ceiling and poor plaster job over cracks above door to adjoining room.)

2021-12-21 07:17:30] Email received from: Penny Vance <Penny.Vance@drewcentral.org>: Mr. Monroe,
I guess the real issue with my stay was what I expected out of a $400 a night hotel.  We came in for the game, and had never been to Green Bay before.  Due to flight changes made by Delta, we ended up flying in on Friday instead of the original Saturday night.  Therefore, we had to stay at another hotel, we chose the Whyndham, it was $89.  We were able to utilized their shuttle service, (masked and vaccinated, they say it helps) and the staff gave us several hints and tips for navigating and eating in Green Bay. 
When I made the reservation at Hyatt, I called instead of making it on-line so I could talk to a human.  I was told there was an air-port shuttle and I was also told the hotel was in walking distance to the stadium.  Now maybe the person I spoke to was in Singapore, I don't know, but neither of those things panned out.
As I have done some traveling during the pandemic, at most hotels if you request housekeeping, the hotel will provide it.  
The room temperature was not able to be regulated correctly, and it was stifling in our room.  We did manage to open the sliding door and that helped somewhat.
As to the front desk, it wasn't so much that when I asked a question, they refused to answer, it was more the lack of a helpful attitude, as was not the case at Whyndham, were they seemed happy to offer help with things I didn't even really know I needed to know.  The Hyatt staff did however agree to hold our bags on Monday, after check-out, when we took our stadium tour before flying out.
Thank you for your concern, 
Penny Vance

2021-12-18 21:22:57] Email received from: Karl Keener <karl.keener@gmail.com>: Good Evening Andrew,
Perhaps I should start from the beginning. Before I made the reservations I check ed out bth the Hyatt and Hotel.com websites. We had stayed at this hotel. few times some years ago and enjoyed our stays. What I saw on the website were some great photos of beautifully well-lit and furnished rooms. I also specifically looked for restaurant and bar information because I knew we would be arriving in the evening. There was no indication that the restaurant and bar are closed on Mondays and Tuesdays;we arrived Monday evening, 12/13.
If you have not seen it lately you should look at room 801. Be careful as you walk in as the carpeting is loose and literally has waves of excess carpet. As I am a business man I expected in a King room of that size and price a desk and chair or some kind of work station; 801 has neither. 
My wife and I both like to read when we go to bed but as you will notice there is a reading lamp on only one of the two night stands. As for the furniture, there is a large over-sized sofas/sectional but no tables to place something to eat or drink. 
Over the years I have stayed at many Hyatt Regencies and this is by far the worst of any Hyatt or other well respected hotel I have encountered. 
When ones goes downstairs in search of food the Market is the only option on Mondays and Tuesdays, and every time I was down there it was not staffed. Therefore I searched around looking for some thing edible and then had to take it to the front desk to have it charged to my room.
I could go on and on, but I’ve already wasted far too much time and money on your hotel. When I said “everything could be improved”, I was not kidding. I know Covid has impacted every one but we have stayed in other hotels in the past 20 months and they are all doing a much better job of accommodating their guests that the Hyatt Regency in Green Bay.
If I was the General Manager or Hyatt Corporate I would be making a lot of changes from top to bottom.
Respectfully,
Karl Keener

column65:
When checking in, we were surprised to hear that rooms would only be cleaned every fourth day, which was not noted when I booked through the Hyatt website.  In my other travels during covid, alternate days or every third day are common, but i've never heard of fourth day.  We stayed 6 days in the hotel, and despite asking multiple times, the room was never cleaned.  I eventually had to beg at the front desk, and get MUCH pushier than i felt comfortable being, to ask for at minimum some fresh towels and shampoo.  Towels and shampoo were left in a garbage bag outside the door of the hotel room.  
I am disgusted that despite picking the date during check in, asking at the front desk again that morning and confirming two time slots available, and then going to the front desk again the next day after asking the housekeeping staff directly, there was no attempt to clean the room, and the front desk staff seemed to think asking for a cleaning 5 days into a stay was an imposition, and they continuously asked if i wanted a special treatment, when i was very clear that i just wanted a normal cleaning in the middle of my 6-day stay, as i had been promised during check-in.  
I've stayed at Hyatt hotels from Seattle to the UK, including planning corporate events, and have always had an excellent experience.  This was more like what I'd expect from a Motel 6.  I will never stay at this particular hotel again, though i will not hold this experience against the Hyatt chain as a whole.

column250: Nothing special how I felt cared about.  Akward front door entrance, crowded with luggage carts.  Our room was not well prepared or inspected before we arrived .  Paid extra for upgrade .. it was dirty, dusty, no tissues, in room phone battery dead - we needed to call front desk as HVAC vent was vibrating and it kept us awake most of the night.  Normally we LOVE Hyatt … this was a disappointment!
The stay was fine. I had a sense that you were being more careful regarding the pandemic than most Green Bay businesses, but it was otherwise a typical hotel stay?

Mr. Jennings, I do apologize that you were caught off-guard by our restaurant being closed during your stay.  We, like many businesses, are so short staffed that we are unable to remain open during all desired hours of operation.  Though we are normally open in our Pub Monday-Saturday evenings, due to special circumstances, we did not have the staffing availability to be open on the night of December 1st.  I am sorry for any inconvenience this may have caused you.  In respect to our corporate mask policy, I am sorry that your personal beliefs do not align with our precautionary measures for the safety of our guests.  It is Hyatt's purpose that, "We care for people so they can be their best,"  and with this in mind, we adhere to the CDC's current masking guidelines which state, "If you are fully vaccinated, to maximize protection and prevent possibly spreading COVID-19 to others, wear a mask indoors in public if you are in an area of substantial or high transmission."  Green Bay is currently listed as an area of high transmission, so until conditions change, we will take every measure to ensure the safety and wellbeing of all of our guests.  

If you have any questions for me or if there is any additional feedback that you wish to provide in regards to how we can better exceed your expectations in the future, please feel free to reach out to me directly. Our repeated errors had apparently worked out in your favor as you didn't get charged for parking. The only exception is when a guest books at a negotiated/contracted rate where parking is included in the rate or when you achieve Globalist status within World of Hyatt and are redeeming points for your stay. I apologize for our past errors leading you to believe that parking fees were not standard, but at least our errors ended up being to your benefit in the end.

As of right now, the CDC recommends that even fully vaccinated individuals, "Wear a mask indoors in public if they are in an area of substantial or high transmission." 2021-11-30 11:35:44] Email received from: Kristine Lendved <klendved@cable.wislib.org>: Dear Mr. Monroe...
Why, thanks...I am grateful for your follow-up!
Very pleased to hear your toilet height is due to be re-sized. I would think that many people will appreciate that!
And, yes, the beds, once in them, were comfortable. And beautifully made, with quilt tucked between the sheets. But, yeah, hard to get in and out of. I would remind you that people sometimes people sit on a bed as part of the dressing process. With there, also, being no chair in the room, there was no good spot to prop oneself. (since beds too high to be able to seat oneself on them.) 
If I made a complaint about customer service, I must've hit the wrong button. It was fine. Certainly no negatives!
The food...well, perhaps I make an assumption I should not when I assume the Hyatt does the catering for the KI Center. I was there as an attendee of the Wisconsin Library Assn Conference and, thus, ate 3 lunches there, from uninspiring to truly dreadful. If I am wrong about Hyatt catering KI events, please accept my apology on that score. Another day I went to your little "store" for more caffeine and some breakfast...and walked away, after waiting 15 minutes, for what turned out to be burned coffee and a dry muffin. The last time I attended a library conference at the same location, I seem to recall the food was tremendous. 
The World of Hyatt thing...I have a vague memory of something about that from a wedding I attended in Chicago some years ago...So, it may date from that time...and your customer service certainly made no mistake in checking status on that, etc.
I lived in Green Bay for a number of years, so, usually when I visit the city I stay with friends! But, this time, appreciated the convenience of proximity to the conference...and also the reasonable room rate for a suite. If I found myself in need of a place to stay, I would absolutely consider the Hyatt. I think that it's quite attractive, well-located and comfortable. 
Cheers and best,
Kristine Lendved

2021-12-01 08:06:02] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Good Morning, Mr. Perl, 

Please allow me to introduce myself. My name is Andrew Monroe, I am one of the Rooms Supervisors here at the Hyatt Regency Green Bay. I am reaching out to you this morning to thank you for taking the time to complete our online survey. It is the feedback from our valued guests such as yourself, which assists us in improving our overall customer service and guest experience. We here at the Hyatt Regency Green Bay take pride in providing both authentic service and clean, comfortable accommodations, however based on your response we have room for improvement. 

Mr. Perl, I do apologize for the fact that we are still only able to provide limited housekeeping service currently.  It boils down to several factors.  First we are still working at maintaining social distancing, as we are still in the midst of a pandemic and the safety of our guests and colleagues is our first priority.  At the same time, just like so many other businesses right now, we have not been able to get our staffing levels to where they need to be if we would even hope to be able to provide daily service to all of our guests.  Though it may have been a slower day, if we wished to provide regular housekeeping as we did before the pandemic hit, our room attendants that we do have, would all have to be working 7 days a week and I can only imagine how  many hours every day they'd have to be here just to finish that heavy of a workload.  Our room attendants, on an average day, currently have to clean 15 or more guest suites.  Some of those suites can take up to an hour due to the degree of consideration many people lack based on the state they leave their rooms in.   I hope you are better able to understand why we yet have limited housekeeping services.  

On another note, Mr. Perl, I can see from your feedback that your experience with our Customer Service as well as our Food & Beverage and Breakfast teams all failed to hit the mark.  If you can provide me with any additional feedback as to what went wrong or where we fell short of your expectations, I'd greatly appreciate it. 

If you have any questions for me or if there is any additional feedback that you wish to provide in regards to how we can better exceed your expectations in the future, please feel free to reach out to me directly. I look forward to hearing back from you at your earliest convenience. Once again, thank you for your time and response.

Sincerely,

Andrew Monroe
Rooms Supervisor
Hyatt Regency Green Bay
Andrew.Monroe@hyatt.com

2021-12-01 09:04:08] Email received from: David Perl <drjperl@gmail.com>: Good morning Andrew,
I am adding answers to your questions below, but let me start with the fact
that I completely understand that we are living in a challenging time, and
bringing on and keeping good employees without a pandemic is difficult at
best. I have no doubt that the drop in service capabilities you are
suffering are on par with other hotels in the area. I also believe honest
feedback is the best way to know where you are and where you need to focus
to improve.
As a guest, I don't get to see the drama unfolding in the back office, but
that is a good thing. I did provide feedback based on my
long-term expectations of your brand as I find that to be more helpful in
my own business to understand how we are recovering from the past couple of
years.
General Cleanliness: Main areas were clean, but corners had collected
dust/dirt, and some surfaces were sticky. Banisters were really dusty. Not
Earth-shattering, but cleanliness issues like this often lead to
second-guessing the trust we place in food safety, etc.
Limited Housekeeping: I have no view of the rooms that had not been cleaned
yet from previous days etc. I did see staff there, but I did not see them
not working. Sory for the double negative, but my point is that they were
busy. My initial assessment was based on the nearly empty parking lot when
we arrived Tuesday night and not being more than 30% full until Friday. I
had not allowed for a backlog of work to be completed.
Front Desk: Outstanding. Good ambassadors for your brand. They were very
respectful, helpful, and efficient.
Breakfast dining: This is an area you may want to focus your customer
service efforts. My family and I were greeted with eye rolls a couple of
mornings. The server we had multiple days was clearly unhappy with her job
and while not specifically rude, she did speak to us tersely. It was enough
for my 8-year-old daughter to ask me why the server was so grumpy. I was a
server while in college and know how taxing that job can be. I did tip her
well as I do all service staff because I know they got hit the hardest with
COVID.
Finally, not on your survey but an area that needs to be addressed. The
tile floor around the pool was not level or draining so areas were always
wet and quite slippery. I did not see anyone fall, but I did see several
people slip and catch themselves when walking on the hotel side of the pool.
Reach out if you have any additional questions.
Thank you,
Dave Perl
(618)799-1503

2021-11-26 22:04:57] Email received from: Joe Reimers <omgjonx@gmail.com>: Hello Andrew,
Thanks for reaching out. Please bear in mind that it's been awhile since
I've traveled, and a certain measure of adjusting to the "new normal" has
to be taken into account.
I appreciated the ready availability of masks and hand sanitizer. And while
I recognize the "new normal" does not permit a daily servicing of the room,
an option for a "light" servicing - or even a trash pickup - would be
appreciated. In retrospect, I probably could have called the front desk,
but I was there for a conference and out of my room for a good chunk of the
day. I did take some meals in my room, however, and that caused trash and
recycle to fill rather quickly.
Additionally - and this is a very minor thing, except when it's not - I
found it very difficult to find a place where I could set up the ironing
board close enough to an outlet to be able to iron. The cords on the
in-room irons are extremely short and the open spaces are quite far from
open outlets.
I don't want to give the impression that I'm a complainer. I've stayed at
several Hyatt properties previously, and have come to expect a certain
standard from Hyatt. The Hyatt Regency Green Bay is certainly a nice hotel
and met my standards for hotel room cleanliness and comfort, but seemed
more in line with an Embassy Suites than a Hyatt Regency. I wasn't
displeased or dissatisfied. My demands aren't all that demanding, and if
things truly were subpar, I would have expressed such at the time. Truth be
told, I've been a (voluntary) return visitor to hotels that aren't as nice
as yours. I just don't often hand out "exceptional" scores. Those require
an extra "something" that stands out, that is truly memorable, that is
somehow above and beyond. I didn't really give your staff that much
opportunity to be exceptional. Please rest assured that should I find
myself in Green Bay again, I will keep the Hyatt Regency Green Bay on my
short list of hotels.
Best,
Joe Reimers

column250: Overall my experience was fine. One area that should be improved is paying attention to online reservation requests. I had requested a feather-free room, and a quiet room. I had to call to have my pillows changed twice because the requests were ignored. My room faced Main Street, and was quite noisy. I do appreciate that it was not near the elevators though. I worked with Scott at the front desk, and he was pleasant and apologized when the feather issue was not fixed correctly the first time.

column64: ; ; ; ; ; ;The only problem for me was that I am gluten intolerant, and when the cafe was closed due to lack of staffing, I only had the option of boiled eggs (which I appreciated) and GF potato chips.; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;
column65: The only problem for me was that I am gluten intolerant, and when the cafe was closed due to lack of staffing, I only had the option of boiled eggs (which I appreciated) and GF potato chips.
column250: Signs in elevators, hand sanitizer placed at each elevator and in other places throughout the hotel, distances between tables, etc.

Cared for: Well marked elevator spots; lots of sanitizing stations

Food: did not like eating in lobby; long wait to check out at small market in lobby - muffins were difficult to get too - not enough staff to handle special coffee orders
I locked my key card in the room and was given another immediately. The neighbor's t.v. was overly loud just one night. A number for volume could be posted??

The gym setup and available machines and ammenities was pretty great. I've never stayed in a hotel that had free cold towels and earbuds. That kicked ass. The breakfast staff was very friendly and helpful. The front desk could have a bell or some way to get ahold of staff. I went to purchase something later at night and had to wait almost ten minutes before being able to get my food. The lobby music could be heard in the rooms, which was annoying. There's also green scum or something growing on the windows in the pool area.

column64: ; ; ; ; ; ;There was no desk or desk chair in the room, so to work, I had to sit on a ottoman with my computer on a beside table and it was very uncomfortable.  The room was very dark unless all lights were on, the hallways and lobby were also very dim and the carpet in the room was so loose there were several ripples in the carpet.  hotel needs an upgrade for sure.; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;

I'm also sorry to hear about the quality of your meal at Pub 333.  If this ever occurs again, I recommend saying something to your server right away.  That not only gives the restaurant the opportunity to prepare something more to your liking, but also many times, after speaking to a manager, many restaurants will also comp your meal or make some concession for your inconvenience.  I am glad, however, to hear that we recovered from that failure during breakfast.  

If you have any questions for me or if there is any additional feedback that you wish to provide in regards to how we can better exceed your expectations in the future, please feel free to reach out to me directly. column239: The lighted mirror in the bathroom didn’t work. The paint in the bathroom was peeling in several places.
column250: Going into the elevator, we made room for a staff member. She said she wasn’t allowed to ride with hotel guests.

I felt cared for when one of the front desk ladies made my coffee in the morning. God bless her! Took the time and made me coffee. It was much appreciated. Something that could be improved is being more firm on guests wearing masks. No one except for less than 10% (including the workers) wore masks! Definitely not used to it.

Cared For- When checking in, the person checking us in saw that I was wearing a Seattle Seahawks jersey. He volunteered to tell me how to catch the free shuttle to the game. Very nice and appreciated!  Improvement- Enforcement of mandatory wearing of masks by guests in public areas!!!

column250: After the football game we tried to eat in the restaurant. Staffing was so short that we would have never been served. Help is short handed but those that were there did a great job.

column250:
The wait staff at the bar & breakfast worked tirelessly & should be recognized.  I didn’t care to be pre-charged the entire amount for the days before. Secondly, upon checking in my credit was again pre-charged $120 “in case” there were “ Incidental” charges. Ludicrous!!
The building had a water pressure issue. Obviously, the booster pump needed repair. Other items were also in need of repair.  
I recognize during this time those items may slip, but the practice of pre-changing is poor business.

We appreciated that employees were wearing masks.  An improvement--I made a mistake and booked the wrong date when I made the reservation.  I called within two minutes upon realizing my error to change the dates.  Although the guest service representative changed the date for me, she would not honor the price I originally paid for the room (which was the same price my corrected date was listed for online).  It added $150 onto the price, which seems steep.

column77:
Right downtown, perfect location for 2 day visit for family/friends.
Rooms are exceptionally large and comfortable
Attentive bar tenders were really nice and great to talk with and share experiences
Parking should be free at these prices, but perhaps in the future mngt will wise up on that.

column77: I prepaid for our 3-day stay, booked it back in June. I called to change our reservation by 1 day, but made it VERY clear we still needed it for the other 2 days. I understood that I wouldn't be reimbursed for the one night I had to cancel, and that is fair as that was on my end. Received an email confirming my CHANGED reservation, but Hyatt Green Bay CANCELLED my ENTIRE PREPAID STAY OF 3 DAYS. We arrive to check in and they stick us in a room half the size of what I reserved, literally ruining the family plans we had made several months before. I will never trust another Hyatt with my travel needs again.

2021-11-17 05:17:51] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Good Morning Mr. Robinson, 

Please allow me to introduce myself. My name is Andrew Monroe, I am one of the Rooms Supervisors here at the Hyatt Regency Green Bay. I am reaching out to you this morning to first of all thank you for taking the time to complete our online survey. It is the feedback from our valued guests, such as yourself, which assists us in improving our overall customer service and guest experience. We at the Hyatt Regency Green Bay take pride in providing both authentic service and clean, comfortable accommodations, however; based on your response, we have room for improvement. 

As you are aware, the average rate for a hotel room in Green Bay on Packers home-game days can be anywhere from $250 if you book early, up to as much as $700 per night before taxes.  There have been times when properties that nowhere near rival our accommodations have charged as much as $300+ per night.  It's simply a case of supply and demand when it comes to the going rate for a hotel room when the Packers are playing at Lambeau Field, but I am sorry to know that the value of our property isn't apparent especially during a special event weekend, where the supply of rooms with the amenities that we offer is so limited.  It's thanks to feedback from our guests such as yourself that we are able to improve and increase the perceived value of what we have to offer.  

On another note, Mr. Robinson, If you care to share any more detailed feedback on how we could have better met and exceeded your expectations in regards our accommodations and what you believe is in need of updating, I would greatly appreciate it.  At the same time, Mr. Robinson, it appears that your experience during breakfast and in general with our Food & Beverage team was less than exceptional.   If you can provide any details on how we fell short of your expectations so we can improve for the future, it would also be appreciated.  Additionally, if you have any preferences for any future accommodations, I'd like to be informed of those as well so you can be as comfortable as possible during your stay at any Hyatt property.

I would like to extend my gratitude for you taking your time to provide your feedback and look forward to hearing back from you at your earliest convenience.  Once again, thank you for your time and your response.

Sincerely,

Andrew Monroe
Rooms Supervisor
Hyatt Regency Green Bay

column250: My wife and I are both 79 yrs old.  Your hotel is not designed or equipped to accommodate people our age.  The bed was so high you practically had to be a high school high jumper to get in.  It was thigh high on my wife.  She also has bad knees and could not climb up the stool that was in the room.  She slept on the couch.  The bathroom had additional problems.  There was absolutely nothing to hold on to while getting in or out of the tub.  A simple hand rail would be very helpful and substantially reduce the risk of falling.  My wife felt completely unsafe to attempt a shower.  Also in the bathroom, the toilet was several inches below even the height of a standard toilet.  As you should know, handicap toilets are several inches higher than a standard toilet, so the toilet you have in most of your rooms is probably 4-6" too low.  I know we did not rent a handicap accessible room, but the equipment in this room was below any standard of safety or comfort even non-handicapped people expect in a public facility.

It was a pleasure speaking with you this morning, as brief as it was.  I want to take a moment to offer my sincerest apologies for your less than positive experience with us.  We appear to have fallen short of even our own standards in many ways with you.  First I'd like to address the matter of Evan's medication and the next steps regarding that.  Now that I have the shipping address, we are going to have that sent out today and will be shipping it overnight to the address provided.  As soon as the shipment is scheduled, you will be receiving an e-mail from with the tracking number.  I am very sorry for any distress this has caused you both as I understand how crucial certain medications can be for one's wellbeing.  Please accept my apologies for the whole fiasco that took place.  Nothing should have happened the way it did.  

In regards to our housekeeping staff barging in the room when I remember personally that your reservation had a late check-out established on it, well it's purely unacceptable.  Our Executive Housekeeper is already aware of what happened and should have already addressed it with her department.  As for your noise issues, I'm sorry to know that your peace was disrupted so rudely and that we did not effectively address this with the culprits who were the source of the issue.  Our security staff is normally far more aggressive in handling complaints of that fashion and I'm so sorry they did not perform with their usual vigor.  I'm glad to know that Scott at least provided a more favorable experience to accent your stay with.  He is actually our new Front Office Manager and is turning out to be a fantastic addition to our team.  We're lucky to have him.

I hope you will accept my most sincere apology for the multiple aspects in which we fell short of your expectations for the Hyatt name.  I have already awarded 8,000 points back to your World of Hyatt account this morning and the hotel will cover the charges to ship Evan's medication to you overnight as well.  Once again I would like to thank you for your time and for your feedback and hope we will get the opportunity to provide you with a better experience some day down the road.

If you have any further feedback you wish to provide regarding your experience or if you have any questions for me whatsoever, please don't hesitate to reach out to me directly.  Again, thank you.

In the spirit of hospitality,

Andrew Monroe
Rooms Supervisor

2021-11-09 06:42:28] Email received from: Melissa Kaatz <melissakaatz@yahoo.com>: Andrew,Thank you for the email.  In regards to the room temperature - we did not contact the front desk because we had our dog with.   Any stranger in the room would not have gone over well, so we dealt with the problem.  It's unfortunate that at check out no staff member asked how my stay was.  The woman next to me checking out was asked how her stay was and she also shared that her room was extremely warm.  The front desk person apologized and offered to provide a refund on all her parking for the inconvenience.  She was never asked why she didn't report it to the front desk.  There seems to be a lacking of consistency in your process.  It was quite upsetting to hear that offered to the person right next to me, when the gentleman had just told me that there could be nothing done with our room rates - they were "locked in".  Yet he could have offered a different fee reduction.  You can see how that would offend a customer.I'll make note of your recommendation for the breakfast..  We purchased the breakfast option not knowing that we would be ordering off the menu.  Had we not done the booking price for breakfast, we would have spent even more on breakfast, as a family of 5 by ordering off the menu each morning.  I understand now how your establishment works in this regard.For the parking, I was able to find a spot each night because I literally sat in my running vehicle for 30 minutes waiting for someone to leave so I could park.  You need to be upfront with customers.  When I checked in, I should have been told that the lot often fills to capacity due to other events in the facility and I may need to park across the street.  That is a much different approach than coming back at 9 pm to not being able to find a place to park and then being told I have to park across the street!  I work in a business where customer service is what we strive for - you need to be upfront with customers and share the why.  Just being told "no" and after the fact, does not leave customers in a good place.  Thank you for listening.  I guess I'm upset over these issues because I thought I was signed up at a higher end establishment and none of my experience felt like that.Melissa Kaatz    On Tuesday, November 9, 2021, 05:19:23 AM CST, Andrew Monroe <hyattguestfeedback@clients.medallia.com> wrote:

Thank you very much for your feedback and follow up on this matter.  I
filled out the survey before my wife called and talked to one of your
employees about the breakfast situation and they proceeded to refund
my account.  I was shocked to see the breakfast charge on my bill as the
employee who worked with my wife apologized and said she would credit the
breakfast charge.
The details of the breakfast situation are as follows:
   - My wife arrived at breakfast to not be greeted by anyone.  There were
   two servers working the breakfast room and not one greeted her or
   acknowledged that they would be right with her.  I understand there is a
   shortage of workers when it comes to hostess/servers and I understand that
   there will be wait.  But waiting for 20 minutes to just be acknowledged is
   not good.
   - My wife walked to the front desk and asked who do I have to get in
   touch with to get some breakfast?  The front desk person said the servers.
   So my wife went back and finally waved one of the servers down, she advised
   them that she would like to place a togo order.  The female server provided
   my wife with a slip to order and this is when things turn from bad to
   worse.  After receiving the slip and deciding on what we wanted for
   breakfast the server never returned back to take the order!  So it took
   another 20 mins for my wife to flag someone else down to take our order who
   was the other server.
   - So now after waiting 15 minutes after the food order was placed, the
   original girl server comes back and asks my wife if she's ready to place
   her order.  Now this is 35 mins AFTER she was originally given the order
   slip to place her order.  My wife tells her that she already placed the
   order with the other server.
   - After finally taking our order it took another 45 mins for them to
   make the food and hand us our order.  Again, I understand that kitchen
   staff are severely understaffed right now but from the moment my wife
   arrived to place a togo order to when she was able to walk out with her
   order it took an hour and 25 mins total time.
   - When the order was finally done my wife took the order up to our hotel
   room, only to find out the order was incomplete!  She ordered two sides of
   bacon and that wasn't included.  So she was beyond upset at this moment and
   she didn't want to risk going back down to the breakfast area only having
   to now wait to get this fixed while our kids have not had breakfast yet.
   So she called down to the front desk and spoke with Becky and voiced her
   frustration.  She said it's completely frustrating  to wait so long and
   only to find out that your order is missing pieces.  Becky apologized for
   the situation and said that she will have them remake the missing items and
   that she will credit the breakfast for us.
The hotel experience was world class and my family really enjoyed your
amenities but the whole breakfast situation really left a sour taste.  I
just wanted to let you know so this doesn't happen again to any other
guests.  Please let me know if you have any additional questions or
comments.

What a surprise to hear from you.
The one thing I missed telling you about is that the mattresses needed to
be flipped, at least in room 621. The mattress was very comfortable, but
people tend to sleep on the "inside edge" so you feel you are "downhill."
As to the food, those who made the arrangements may have opted for the
"economy choices" during our breaks. The coffee was quite good, but the
selection of sweat rolls was very limited. A lot of places put out a
combination of sweat rolls, including chocolate selections, and then, for
the more healthy-minded guests, something like muffins. The noon lunch I
had was pretty mediocre. Chicken a bit "rubbery"; there was like a tomato
soup that was nothing to write home about.
All in all, however, for an older hotel the Hyatt is really not showing its
age. The room I had was huge (about as big as my son's coop apt in NYC
where he and his wife resided up until two years ago!). It has been very
well-maintained and everything was very clean. And being a person who is
immunocompromised, I very much appreciated the masking and distancing that
was required. It would not hesitate returning. (For $82/night the court
system -- and the taxpayers -- got a very good deal.
Robert E. Kinney

Otherwise, it was a beautiful room and facility.
Nothing love staying at this place

column250: Your policies on COVID don't make sense.  You want people with communicable diseases to stand in an elevator together and stand apart according to a little diagram?  How about people who take personal responsibility for their well-being carry on with life and those with a reason to be extra careful wait for an empty elevator?  The excuse staff gave us was "this is what the hotel association recommends." I don't blame the staff, but the policies were non-sensical and didn't stand muster to reason.  I'm guessing that you don't do this level of "precaution" for the flu... which kills more people each year.  So, unless this is a permanent change for ALL diseases, knock it off.  The hotel was very clean and I felt like people were respectful... but the corporate covid signage everywhere demanding that everyone mask up and "be safe" was silly.

column64: ; ; ; ; ; ;The nickel and dime costs were very frustrating. Parking charges were not disclosed at check-in. We were just told to swipe our key to get in and out. column77:
Traveled for a work conference. Late check in (8:45pm). Mass are mandated at all times in the hotel--all public areas. Understandable if in an elevator or close proximity to others, but should not need one when walking through and no one is near. 

Asked at check-in if restaurant was open, informed yes. Attempted to order at 8:55pm and no response from restaurant. Contacted front desk and was informed "they must have closed."

Room was clean and nice. Updated. On 8th floor. Windows must be thin because could hear road traffic outside all night. 

Bathroom cleanliness was subpar. Toilet seat was stained and pitted. Gross. Long hairs stuck to ceiling and walls. 

More attention to the little things would help. Not worth a stay for work travel.
column239: Bathroom toilet seat was stained and pitted. Gross. Bathroom walls and ceiling had long hairs stuck to it.
column250: Mask mandates are excessive when no around other people. Kitchen closed earlier than indicated. Room bathroom cleanliness subpar.

column64:
; ; ; ; ; ;Compared to other Hyatt Regency properties we have stayed in, this one is in need of an update.  Although the room was clean, the furniture was old and scratched, sofa was stained, lamp shades were bent, curtains were frayed and the bathroom had a mildew smell.  Bar/pub open hours were minimal which was very disappointing.

I do want to mention that the front desk clerk, Tobi, was always very helpful and attentive.; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;

The packaged breakfast awful, especially the egg muffin the last day of the conference. The conference meal on Saturday night had horribly dry chicken. My room had mold in the bathroom on the walls near the tub and the ceiling, room 532 I think.  The up side, the rooms are spacious and comfortable, clean linens.  The staff on the day of check out was nice and the Starbucks girl was nice.

column64: ; ; ; ; ; ;I thought I had indicated a need for a handicapped-accessible room when I made our reservations months ago. I called twice in September to check on this. I was told by a reservationist that it was taken care of. When I called again, it wasn't. This reservationist assured me that he had taken care of it. I was expecting an accessible room. Apparently, taking care of the situation means putting in the request and not verifying that your room request is honored. I wish that had been made clear. I imagine those room fill up fast and understand why one wasn't available for us. The front desk clerks made sure that we got a shower chair in a timely manner. column250: make breakfast hours accurate.  We were told breakfast was only on Saturday and Sunday, so made other plans for Monday and Tuesday and when we came back from breakfast elsewhere, saw that breakfast area was open.  Carpet and drapes were old.  We had a balcony we could go on and it was disgusting.  You couldn't even open the door because of all the dead bugs and webs on glass and on the balcony itself.  There was a empty beer bottle and some cigarette butts outside on the balcony also.  We had a few spiders in our room probably because of it.   I am an Explorist and this was the first time I was not welcomed as one and was not offered my water when we came in.  Had to ask for it ourselves.

column250: The air conditioner in my room was not working correctly. I reported it the next morning and they said that they would look into it. There was no change when I came back that night. The next morning I reported it again and two security officers showed up and told me that that AC was working find and it was because it was to hot the day before. I disagreed with them so they gave me a fan. I reported it again and was told sorry.
Jesse and the staff went over and above to help make my girlfriends birthday amazing!  We love GB!

I came in later in the evening and had food delivered to my room - they very clearly made sure I knew what the current processes were so it was very easy. I stayed in room 606 - the fan for the air conditioner was pretty loud - it didn't bother me so much but might bother the next guest.
Overall cleanliness

column250: During my stay I requested a later check out time due to obligations that I had at the conference center that day. I was disappointed that it was declined due to high occupancy - however, this was not what I was offended by. The individual who was managing the front desk was outright rude to me and offered no explanation nor options to meet my needs while on site. When I attempted to explain what it was that I needed and that I would need at least until 11:30 to gather my things (it was 10:55 at the time) he treated me as though I was a problem and told me that "that was the latest he would allow". As though someone would come to the room to physically remove me if I wasn't out by then. Although I have stayed at this hotel many times and usually prefer Hyatt, this experience was very negative and has left me less than eager to do so again.

column250:
Your Hyatt Regency property along with others post-covid are extremely behind their peers (Marriott and Hilton). Why don't you have glasses in the room? Instead you use paper and plastic as though you were an Econolodge (while charging 5star prices). You use the excuse that you are trying to protect customers from covid--not so. You are really just being performative and jump-starting the global warming crisis.
If you really cared you would demand vaccination proof to enter your property. That way you would protect your guests and employees. It appears you are padding your bottom line with no actual protection and providing 1star amenities. Worst breakfasts ever!!
Provide information in room for on site dinner & breakfast times with menu.

It's time to move on.  Most businesses are customer optional on masks, etc and respect that wish.  Mandating only created a secluded environment that was met with frustration or animosity which only created an awkward experience despite the high level of service.
I love the Hyatt it’s the best hotel in town.

column64: ; ; ;air conditioning and fan were sub par; ; ;The room space was very accommodating.  However the room location was one of the worst possible and VERY noisy.  We had a room that faced the busy street and hear VERY LOUD traffic noise well into the early morning hours.  My one daughter that can sleep through anything, couldn't sleep.  We were also right across from the elevator.  Hotel did not seem busy to fill rooms that were more optimal.  Also, I had called to get a group rate through UW Green Bay when making the reservation.  Reservations call center gave me a discounted rate of $94.  When I called the hotel directly, I was quoted a  rate of $107.  Others in the group had a rate of $87.  I forwarded my email to the front desk person, Jett Martin, who said would talk with hotel manager.  3 days later I still have not heard anything.  Also was not told by reservations desk that there was a $10 parking fee.  Very disappointing.; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;

We are in the middle of the pandemic.  You have signs saying masks are mandatory in public areas of the property.  You have staff saying that to guests checking in.  Yet, nobody is enforcing this. column64: ; ; ;I shared that some of the outlets and lamps didn't work, along with the exhaust fan in bathroom. Other than that, everything was good.; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;
column77: We stayed in a suite for three nights Labor Day Weekend 2021. The hotel is beautiful. We have stayed three times prior. We have three teen boys and my husband and I. Make sure if you have more than two people, you ask for extra towels, soap, shampoo, coffee, hangers, etc. We only had enough for one, maybe two and had to ask. The hotel was clean and had a nice pool, hot tub, steam room, coffee shop, restaurant, bar, etc. Great place to stay with an awesome location walkable distance to the boardwalk on the river with shops and restaurants. We have stayed three times now and will stay every time we visit Green Bay to see my In-Laws.
column239: I shared that some of the outlets and lamps didn't work, along with the exhaust fan in bathroom. Other than that, everything was good.
column250: We had five of us in a suite. My husband, myself and our three teen boys. We had to ask for extra towels, shampoo, soap and hangers. The bathroom exhaust fan didn't work, some of the outlets didn't work, and there were not enough plugs for the lamps if you needed to plug anything in at all besides in the bathroom, which one of the outlets didn't work in there. Besides those tiny issues, the major issue was that they charged me the cost of the weekend, plus $100 over for the three night stay on the day we arrived, then charged us upon check out. I didn't know this until the day we returned home from our 8 hour drive and into the next day when I checked the bank. It has double charges pending plus and extra $100 for a deposit I assume? Not happy about that. Our money is tied up and pending, which means I have to wait now after calling the Hyatt to let them know. Not sure how long it will take for the first charges to drop off (which had the extra $100), but when I called, a front desk rep said that it is a deposit and will drop off and only be charged the difference. What difference? I was billed for the three night stay and charged with an actual bill that was sent to my email the day we checked out from the hotel. Why would I be charged twice? And why would I have to wait for it to be cleared and put back into my bank when I was already charged? Not sure if I didn't understand something, but I have NEVER paid double for a hotel and it took four days pending in my account only to be told it will be given back? I am still waiting. Hope it is true, otherwise, I will be one really unhappy customer. With all that being said, the hotel is beautiful and the beds were very comfortable, the rooms are spacious and the amenities like the coffee shop and breakfast and the pool and hot tub, steam room, etc. were all fantastic. The location is also wonderful. You can walk to the boardwalk on the river with many shops and restaurants. Overall we will stay again if the double charge gets taken care of asap. And we now know to make sure we ask for all of the extras to accommodate our family when we arrive.

While overall the Hyatt was good, the food service was not.  In fact, I could not even eat using the Hyatt restaurant or Market even though both were open.  The restaurant was to small and understaffed to handle the Sunday morning breakfast.  After standing in line for 30 minutes, only 2 people were seated.   Ordering to go by phone was not an option.  The Market had 1 person working during rush hour-after another 20-30 minutes waiting in line, she had only made 2 coffees for 1 person.    I literally ordered by Door Dash and received my breakfast before she finished 1 order.    I normally love enjoying breakfast in my room with coffee to quietly get ready for the day, but that was not even possible.   I ate my Door Dash breakfast and left.

column250:
The AC in my first room did not work.  When I called the front desk in the early evening, the person did not offer any apology and was not proactive in helping me resolve the issue.  Her first option was asking if I wanted a fan.  I told her no, I wanted AC.  Finally sent engineering up to my room - he was an extremely nice person who sincerely was trying to help me. It sounded to me as if the motor in the AC unit was not working and he was going to need to call his boss to find out what to do.  By this time, it was almost 10pm and my AC still did not work.  Front desk said they could "try" to find me another room to "see if that would be better".  I took all my belongings down to the front desk and asked for a new room.  Thankfully that room had working AC.  And it was in much better condition than my first room - which clearly needed some maintenance in the bathroom and the sliding glass door.  I guess the takeaway from all this is that the front desk staff did not demonstrate good customer service that evening, which was incredibly frustrating to me.

On the positive side, the beds were extremely comfortable!

column77: Highly recommend this hotel.  The atrium is beautiful and the room is very spacious (we had 2 Queens with pull out couch). The bathroom was very small in the hotel room but they did a great job with remodeling what they could.
column250: The staff was incredibly helpful and nice. However almost no staff members were wearing masks. At at Hyatt we stayed at night before everyone was wearing masks and Covid precautions were strictly enforced.  It was disappointing to see that was not at all Hyatt locations.  We stayed at Radisson that did not enforce covid precautions either and thought would have brand loyalty to Hyatt but not if it’s not consistent.

My family was not given their breakfast meal tickets upon arrival. They were charged for the meal. I was not asked about or offered parking validation upon checking out. I had to ask about this myself.
Staff was friendly. They were on top of Covid messaging.  I asked where overflow parking was and they didn’t know

column250: Bathrooms could be updated.  Toliets are super low to the ground and should be replaced.   Our fan in our room turned on and off all night and was extremely disruptive to sleep.

It was a bummer to have to pay for parking. I typically don’t have to do that at hotels I’ve stayed in. Seems like a silly thing to have to pay for when paying to stay there. When I checked in, my parking fee was added to my bill. When we left to go the wedding, we couldn’t figure how to get out with paying again. I did talk to the girl at the front desk who was very nice and took it off my sister’s bill who paid for it. So I did appreciate that. But if you’re going to charge for parking, it seems to make sense just to pay when you leave. Other people may not ask and pay extra.

column250: I don't like the $100 cleaning fee and weight limit of the dog. Our dog is well trained, kenneled and on a leash. I'm not sure why we have to pay for this fee for a little area of vacuuming. Felt like the hotel was a little 'meh' in comparison to other regencies I've been to. The room had a lot of condensation in it, and the decor need updating as some of the furnishings saw some ware and tear. I stay at regencies because they're typically more elegant and this was quite disappointing when compared to most.

Front desk staff was very helpful and rooms were very nice and clean. 

Had to wait for simple housekeeping items (coffee refills, extra blankets) for longer then expected.

column64:
; ; ;Hello,

While staying the 15 nights in GB there were a number of issues.  I understand times are difficult still however I hope the time spent on my feedback might improve the Hyatt experience.

Some issues in the room and hotel:

The toilet did not flush, I fixed the chain in the tank

The door did not close properly without slamming and or pushing in the latch area

The dryer on both the 4th and 7th floor require two runs in order to dry clothes, which takes more time and $2 more of quarters each time

The dryer on the 7th floor had some type of sticky substance in it that was all over the clothing 

The beer taps in the hotel pub were out for 3 nights

Three coolers were out of commission for a few days so chicken wings, rueben, etc were not available on the menu 

The initial check in took sometime as it did when I was rebooking my next stay at the front desk.  It was evident that the staff was dealing with a very slow computer system.

Shampoos and conditioner needs to be asked for, sometimes at this location and other Hyatt Regancy locations even if an empty bottle is left on the floor of the bathroom it still is not replaced.

The workout room has the area for the refrigerated towels, however most days none are in the fridge 

Again the staff all seem polite and helpful.  The sales manager Tiffany was very nice and let me borrow a phone charger for a few hours, before I was able to get a replacement for mine.

I hope this feedback helps with future improvements.; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;

column64:
; ; ;We are content and happy Hyatt members and need to bring this to management attention. 

My wife has polio and uses a wheelchair. She works with the United Nation on implementing international disability policy.

We have never complained nor have we ever been disappointed staying with Hyatt’s. We alway leave a $5 to $10 tip cash under our pillow for house keeping. 
We also leave our room pretty much the same as we checked in, all trash in one trash can, dirty towels hanging to dry, the bed 95% made with a note thanking house cleaning with a nice tip under the note by the pillow. 

We have to share that the Green Bay Hyatt Regency Convention Center Hotel, especially the ADA room #701 has changed this excellent track record.

July 22, 2021, My wife and I stayed at the Hyatt Regency Green Bay in a ADA room # 701. A few problems that should be addressed.

The King Bed needs to be replaced ASAP as the left side sinks in the middle. I believe that for many years of people sitting and sleeping on the left side the springs/coils have giving out. FYI, We have a king Hyatt mattress at home.

The microwave is broken, will not heat water. When attempting to use, it smokes, the wires are burning inside and smells like a fire is going to start. I did not unplug as management of house cleaning needs to confirm.

The ADA shower drain needs to be rotor rooter out. The tile shower floor tilts to one side, 1 to 2 gallons of water collects in a puddle and will not drain. The only way to clean up is to use two large towels. This is extreme dangerous for wheelchair users or for anyone with a disabilities. 

The L shape brown couch with a matching otterman. This couch needs to be quarantined or brought to a landfill. There are multiple stains all over this couch. I would guess that it is 20 plus years old. I would request that Hyatt management use a black light to confirm my observation.

We drove all day from MPLS to Green Bay. We check in a little before 4 pm, got to our room about 4pm and construction workers were jack hammering on the side of the building. We were 7 floors above the jack hammering. This was vibrating our room.  I went down and ask the front desk when he thought they would finish he said hopefully 5pm. At 5pm the construction work stopped. 

Oh yea, at or around 4:45pm the fire alarm goes off, I rolled my wife’s wheelchair to the elevator. Where a line of people were waiting with the alarm still ringing. We later learn from a letter from management that  the alarm went off due to construction dust. 

The past 20 years, my wife and I have been staying at many International Hyatt Hotels around the world. We have stayed at the Hyatt in San Francisco, Los Angeles, Hanoi, the Park Hyatt in Saigon, Vietnam, the Jakarta, Indonesia Hyatt, our favorite is the Yogyakarta Hyatt in Indonesia. México City Hyatt, NYC, etc…. etc…. etc….

Thank you for your attention in this important matter. 

Hyatt Member #538499550P

Kindness regards,


David Richard
11735 Moorpark 
Studio City, CA  U.S.A. 91604
(818) 448-2190 Mobile

column250: When we complained to a manager, she listened and took care of the problem.  However, there was a great deal of things that were not what expected before.  I was told the parking was $5, it was $10.  I was told that the breakfast was a buffet, it was a VERY rigid a la carte menu.  For example, we couldn't substitute pepsi for a coffee or orange juice.  We had NO IDEA that there would not be daily housekeeping.  We have stayed in other hotels since COVID and had daily housekeeping.  It is not the Hyatt standards from before COVID.
Employees very friendly. Everything was good.

Best price even when it was quoted by mistake honoring it.

Sofa bed springs need to be checked and adjusted
Room service every 4 days was a stretch.  Most hotels are 2-3 days.

column77: Came in town for the weekend and everything was better than I expected.  The rooms were large, clean and fully stocked.  Staff was both helpful and friendly every time I saw them.  I honestly couldn’t believe how low the room rate was for what you receive.

column64: ; ; ; ; ; ;We come here often. It is our favorite hotel in the Green Bay area. I come here for conferences at work and have returned for special date nights with my wife. I was admittedly disappointed at check-in. I specifically asked for a top floor room looking west towards the river area when I booked the room via hyatt.com when we checked in the clerk seemed not to even know we had made that request and then told us no rooms were available. I had reserved a King corner and even said a non-corner room would be fine even not looking out towards the river just on the top floor. She politely told us none were available. I only saw one person exit a room on the 8th floor during our stay. It didn't appear that anyone else was staying on the top floor. Could be I am wrong but it seemed a room may have been available and just wasn't offered. The front desk clerk was very nice and polite (as always) it just left a bad feeling about it in our normally wonderful past visits to the Hyatt GB.; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;

2021-07-14 15:11:36] Email received from: C Staniak <cs4pack@hotmail.com>: As far as the breakfast goes, it was adequate. My omelet was meager in terms of ingredients and cheese. The potatoes were ok. It did give me the feeling of being somehow prepared beforehand and reheated but I'm sure that I was just imagining that. Most importantly, the coffee was not good. It was served in a disposable (Styrofoam? Paper?) cup. I was never offered a refill and would have turned it down regardless. That alone was reason for me to go out to a legit restaurant for breakfast.
The parking situation is ridiculous. When I returned to the hotel on both Friday and Saturday evenings, there was not a space too be found. As a registered guest, that irritated me a great deal. And then you have the gall to charge me for parking. Again, ridiculous. It angers me just thinking about it again.
The pool was nice. The room, though uncomfortably warm, was nice and clean. My bed was comfortable. The only contact with staff in the four days I was a guest was at check-in and they were both pleasant. I did appreciate the convenient little market in the lobby. 
Aside from the breakfast and parking, it was a good experience. Will I recommend your hotel to others? Likely yes if for no other reason the location is excellent.
Thanks for your concern,
Christopher

column77:
I have stayed at this hotel for many years, it has a great location, beautiful spacious rooms and great design. But over the years since the last renovation, it has fallen into disrepair. I do not want to give negative characteristics to the place where I spent many wonderful hours, but I was ashamed of its appearance. But mattresses and linens are in good condition though. Excellent customer service.

All these years breakfast was excellent, but due to dilapidation I did not want to spend a single extra minute in the hotel and went to have breakfast elsewhere. However, I heard from other guests that the breakfast was excellent.

Owners, do your hotel renovation at last, it deserves it.

2021-06-22 21:28:50] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Dear Ms. Kluck,

Thank you for sharing your feedback.

I apologize for the inconveniences you experienced during your stay. I will touch on each of your concerns. I have shared your feedback with our team so that we can improve how we handle situations, have our rooms in working/clean order, and assign room requests. First, our thermostat system can sometimes be a challenge and while the building was in a cooling mode during your stay, it did struggle at times to cool below 67* across the hotel. Second, our Security Team is limited and cannot be everywhere at the same time. If our team came to your room about noise, it was due to a noise complaint from a neighboring room. I sincerely apologize if our team offended you in any way; however, they are required to acknowledge complaints for other guests as well and attempt to maintain quiet hours. We follow the same protocols at many resort and hotel companies in regards to our quiet hours. Lastly, we do our best to honor requests for room placement; however, it is not guaranteed. On busy dates in the hotel, it can be nearly impossible to accommodate. I am sorry that you and your travel companions were down the hall from each other. My team will work to improve our service and be more delicate when responding to noise complaints. We will also consider modifying our quiet hours in the hotel.

As we are still working through recovery from the global pandemic, we are striving to create guest experiences that make you feel welcomed, comfortable, and relaxed. Currently, while there are some procedures that we currently follow that seem like an inconvenience; unfortunately, they are in place while we train our new Colleagues and try to balance experience and efficiency. Thank you for staying with us and for sharing your feedback in our guest survey.

Thank you for choosing to stay with us and for sharing your feedback.

I want to personally apologize for making you feel embarrassed and for not asking more inclusive and welcoming questions. I was asking if we could provide a wheelchair so that we could provide a comfortable stay - not because I felt you were incapable and I am ashamed that I came across as anything else. After reflecting on your note, I will work harder to be more inclusive for our guests and more discreate in the types of assistance I offer. 

In regards to the type of room you were booked into, we do have two rooms in the hotel that have lower beds. In future visits, so that we can ensure a safe and comfortable experience, please let us know you would like a lower bed and we will do our best to accommodate your request. Most hotels in the United States do have these types of rooms set up as their ADA-accessible rooms. We strive to provide access for all of our guests and want to prevent hardships and hinderances during your hotel stay. The last thing you should have to worry about is getting in and out of bed and we will do our best to be as accommodating as we can be so that you can be your best, authentic self.

As a goodwill gesture, I have applied 5,000 points to your World of Hyatt account. These will be reflected online in 3-5 business days. 

Again, I sincerely apologize if I made you feel uncomfortable. We hope that you and your family come back and see us again in the future. If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out. I will be glad to assist you.

column250:
I was asked if I needed a wheelchair just because I was using a cane to walk with (I have mild cerebral palsy and and am missing a joint in one ankle and recently broke the other one at the end of 2019). I think the employee thought they were being helpful so that’s nice. But honestly it made me embarrassed to be using my cane to walk with. One of the team members (Paul) was very helpful in helping us order a pizza.
To be honest the room we stayed in (201) wasn’t exactly comfortable for me in terms of the bed because it was really high off the ground! It was very difficult to get in and out of!!

There was an issue with my payment when I arrived at the hotel-however, the person at the front desk was incredibly helpful and supportive! He helped me solve the issue right away. One of the best experiences I've had at any hotel! Thank you so much!!

column250: At 8am maintenance staff knocked on my door because they said my shower was broken.  They asked if I needed to use the shower. Of course, I needed a shower as I was speaking at an event in 2 hours.  They proceeded to do shower repairs and then informed me they wanted to remove and change my toilet.  I told them to do so after I left the room.  They changed the toilet later.  Left soaking wet dirty towels in the bathroom.   I tried to call the front desk and the phone did not work. I had to go to the desk, wait in line.  They sent someone to clean up the room and replace towels..  As a CEO, I travel extensively and have never had staff doing room maintenance while I was in the room.  No sincere apologies, no offer to move me to another room.  Completely disregard of this extraordinary inconvenience. Would not recommend this hotel to anyone.

2021-05-23 11:03:56] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Dear Mr. Martin, 

Thank you for choosing to stay with us and for sharing your feedback in our guest survey.

I sincerely apologize that your Chromecast and television did not work properly and that we did not replace them like we said we would. I have spoken with our Director of Engineering and we are working with our Teams to ensure we have better communication when it comes to guest's needs. In regards to face coverings in the hotel, during your stay, the CDC reduced regulations for people who are vaccinated and maintained recommendations for those who are unvaccinated. As the news was announced, many guests seemed to hear the news before we did and there was a lot of confusion and difficulty on our end policing it. 

However, since then, Hyatt has made an official statement that masks are recommended but no longer required for vaccinated guests. If a guest is not vaccinated, they are still required to wear a mask. This means that we will keep signage in place but not actively asking guests, aside from check-in or at the desk, to wear masks.

I appreciate you following with mask compliance. As we return to normalcy, we hope that we can lessen restrictions even more so that guests can be safe in our hotels.

If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out - I will be glad to assist you. 

Sincerely,

Paul Zagorski

Thank you for taking the time to share thoughtful and actionable feedback with us in our survey.

I sincerely apologize for the inconveniences you experienced during your stay. To address your concerns, the day prior to your arrival, our Engineering Team had to turn off the water to the entire hotel to repair a water line. Unfortunately, when the water was turned back on, it did cause some harmless discoloration. While we did our best to run the water in as many rooms as we could, unfortunately some may have been missed. I assure you that your room was cleaned the day before you arrived; however, it was unused the evening after the water was shut off and turned back on.

In regards to my Front Desk Team, I am sorry that we did not ask how your stay was or if there were problems to address. We will add that back to our interactions. That had unfortunately slipped out of our minds as in the past year, our guests have been incredibly blunt when there are issues for us to address - but, I don't want you to think that is an excuse. We should be caring for our guests and ensure they are having a seamless and enjoyable stay.

I am glad to hear that the interactions you had with our Team away from the front desk were positive. We must do better all around and I assure you we will.

If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out - I will be glad to assist you.

column250: At 4:00 am on our first night in the hotel I heard dripping in the bathroom. Water was pooling in the light fixture. When touched it streamed out on to the floor. Security came up at 4:15 and said the person above probably took a shower with the curtain out. They could not reach them. The dripping continued throughout the night. My wife and I had an important meeting the next day and did not get back to sleep. The steady stream of water continued the next day and crews interrupted two meeting that I and my wife scheduled. They did the toilet was leaking above and replaced the seal twice. The dripping did not  stop. After a half a day of this my wife called again. We were moved to the room next door. A pipe in the ceiling was leaking and nothing could be done at theat time. We were in no shape for the meeting and events we had to attend. Upon checking out the manager offered a $40 adjustment to our bill. It is our belief the Hyatt should have done a lot more for us than this.  We are not happy. Steve and Beth Zambo sfz36s3w@gmail.com

column250:
After waiting a long time for the breakfast pickup, I realized they had forgotten my daughter's meal. When I went back and told them, the lady apologized profusely and quickly provided the adult meal free of charge to correct the mistake. We were also surprised and impressed by the small splash area which is not advertised on the website.
The only unfortunate thing was that on the day of our checkout our son got stuck in the elevator for over 30 minutes while the engineer rectified the situation. I was disappointed that the manager did not contact us at all during the whole encounter to apologize or check on our son or the other guest's wellbeing.

I was very disappointed that the hot tub was closed - It should have been mentioned when the reservation was made.
I was disappointed that the cleaning staff only comes every 3 days so no cleaning was done nor replenishing of bath towels.

column77:
In the past month I have spent two weekends at this hotel, and both time thoroughly enjoyed my experience. I am a travel advisor who was booking room blocks for a group attending events at the connected convention center. My group/event coordinator (Leslie R) was absolutly fantastic and helped with everything I needed. She accommodated us when one of our events changed venues and helped me put together a very last minute pizza party event in. 

On top of the booking and lead up process running well, the front desk staff was a amazing each and every time I was up there. The rooms and lobby were clean and inviting and extremely spacious.  We had everything we needed onsite and were a short walk to the river and a wonderful little hangot area with a river viewing restaurant. 

Everything about both of our stays was just perfect. I'm truly hoping we have events that bring us here in the future!

column250: During this time of pandemic, your hotel like all other hotels, have cutback/reduced housekeeping on a daily basis. This includes daily cleaning of guest rooms. column64: ; ; ; ; ; ;I enjoyed my stay.  I appreciated the 25% discount for breakfast.  The food was very good.  However when I got ready to pay the bill and put it as a room charge I was SHOCKED.  This is the FIRST hotel that was going to charge me 18% plus some fixed fee to charge breakfast to my room.  I think the total came to $2.16.  I paid with a credit card to avoid the ridiculous fee.  I would like to know the genesis who came up with this idea.  I guess it is like the "occupancy tax" tacked onto your room rate.  I guess the room rate allows you to open the door and look in, but before you can enter you are charged an occupancy tax.  Sure would be nice to see the USA wakeup and do things like they do in Europe.  The rate for the room covers EVERYTHING-all hidden fees even including the 14% VAT!!; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;
