column77: The hotel itself was fine. It was actually quite busy at the hotel with a wedding event going on at the adjacent building, as well as a girls' dance competition during the weekend we stayed. The swimming pool has a limit capacity of 26 people, but this was not respected by the guests nor enforced by the staff. My kids and I tried to time it so that there would be less people in the pool area (or with the 26 ppl capacity) when we went swimming, but people just kept coming into the pool without any regard to the capacity limit. We decided to leave the pool because I felt it was unsafe for myself and my kids. Also, there were groups of people talking to each other without masks in the lobby area and no hotel staff seemed to care to enforce the mask-wearing policies.
column250: Wedding guests staying at the hotel were seen talking in the lobby without masks and I was quite disappointed that the hotel staff did not say anything. There were maybe 6-8 people talking together for 10+ minutes and not one hotel staff enforced the wearing mask policy. Also, my 2 kids wanted to go swimming and noticed that there was a limit of 26 people in the pool area. We waited until the crowds were less and then went swimming. However, after 6pm (after dinner) people began coming in groups and the limit was way beyond 26, closer to 40 or maybe even 50 people. I no longer felt safe, so we left. It would have been nice to see security guards or hotel staff maintaining these safety policies (mask wearing & pool capacity) to make sure all guests feel safe.

2021-04-14 14:23:37] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Dear Mr. Pfeifer,

Thank you for staying with us and for sharing your feedback about your experience.

I sincerely apologize that your room condition was in disrepair. We are working to get back on track for our entire hotel refurbishment now that we are returning to some sort of normalcy with our business. I have also spoken with our Director of Engineering so that his team can fix or touch up what needs repair. 

In regards to the incidental hold, when you arrived to the hotel, we only authorize a credit/debit card for potential incidentals - or - for cash, it is for incidentals and a security deposit. There is not a detailed list of these charges because it is not a charge. It is an authorization/security deposit. It is there in case you charge something back to the room from the Market, Pub333, premium internet, phone calls from the in-room phone, parking fees, etc. The authorization is released to a credit/debit card upon check-out. For cash incidental/deposits, our Housekeeping Team will inspect the room for damages/smoking and if everything is ok with the room, the deposit is returned. 

For the few hotels, like us, that still accept cash at check-in, it is a standard practice. If you use a card at any other Hyatt Hotel worldwide, and nearly every other major hotel chain - including Hilton and Marriott, this is a standard practice. I apologize if it was not made more clear the reasons for this and the details of what is/is not considered an incidental. Also, from what I can see on your hotel statement, you did receive your deposit back. 

I hope that your future stays are more enjoyable and seamless. If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out.

Sincerely,

Paul Zagorski
Front Office Manager
Hyatt Regency Green Bay

Really appreciative of a woman who was overseeing people in common areas without masks and ensuring that they wear one.  I know that her job is a thankless job and I'm sure she has faced unkind words and anger from people who do not agree with the mask policy. However, I am appreciative of this being in place and for people like her who do their job even knowing it is not going to be received well by some people. Thank you for making this an important aspect of your hotels.

I appreciated the communication about how things are modified so I knew what to expect. The only thing that could be improved is the staffing just wasn’t there to be able to accommodate the amount of guests that were there for an event. For example, only one front desk attendant and only 2 servers and there were hundreds of people there. Even so, they did the best with what they had!

Information about some of the extra charges. example parking / dinning. We didn't really have a clear understanding of how this was going to be presented on our bill at the end. Parking was removed because there was no room in the lot and breakfast was included and not attached to our bill. All this was great. However, even though this was the case we never really understood how or if we were being charged.

Thank you for staying with us and for sharing your feedback in our survey.

I sincerely apologize that your room keys stopped working prior to your late check-out time and that you experienced longer than normal wait times at the front desk. We are working to bring staff back and hire more so that we do not have lines at the front desk. I appreciate your understanding as we are still in a global pandemic and working to find a stride with the waves of guests that come and go. Also, our Housekeeping Team did follow proper protocols in that they have no way of verifying names and IDs for particular rooms and as a security precaution, are not allowed to let someone into a room. 

I am sorry that these inconveniences caused you to be late for your daughter's dance group. I have spoken to our IT Manager to ensure when we update rooms for late check-out, that the keys also follow suit. As a goodwill gesture, I am putting an automatic late check-out of 2:00PM on your reservation now. This will ensure that the keys work past noon and it will also allow you some extra time in the room should you need it. 

If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out. We look forward to welcoming you back at the end of April. 

Sincerely,

Paul Zagorski
Front Office Manager
Hyatt Regency Green Bay

Thank you for staying with us and for sharing your feedback in our guest survey.

I sincerely apologize for the inconveniences you experienced during your stay with the bathroom mirror, Chromecast, and parking concerns. I have already spoken with our Executive Housekeeper and she will be working with her team to ensure that little things like fingerprints are not missed. We will also be checking to ensure all of the parts of our Chormecasts are in the room so that future guests can enjoy the connectivity to watch their favorite streaming shows while they travel.

In regards to parking, we charge for parking so that our guests have a secure lot available to them. There are times where we must utilize overflow lots. We offer a reduced rate of $10/night which is less that the City of Green Bay parking lots and other hotels in the area. In addition to this, we offer our World of Hyatt Members discounted parking as a "thank you" and sometimes have promotions that will even offer parking to be included. We have played with the idea of including it in the room rate and we hear concerns that our rates are too high. We also have a number of guests that don't drive to our hotel. They may utilize other transportation services and that may not be wise for them. 

As a goodwill gesture, I have refunded the parking charge from your stay. I have also noted your profile that we will do our best to offer discounted parking during your future visits.

If there is anything else you wish to discuss during your stay, please do not hesitate to reach out.

column250:
I chose the Hyatt because the price was right, I've stayed there in the past, and I liked what they had to offer. The things I liked are how large the rooms are (separate bedroom and living room/kitchen/bar area), they have Chromecasts on all the TV's, the TV in the bedroom looked a lot bigger than the last time we stayed there, they have a light up magnifying mirror in the bathroom, etc. 

The things I didn't like:
Having to pay $10/night for parking (I personally don't think you should have to pay to park at the hotel your staying at, that charge should be included in the room fee. Also, the charge shouldn't be anymore than $5/night!) This time I struggled with the chromecast because the one in the living room wasn't plugged in and someone stoled a piece of it, which made it useless (the part that plugs into the wall). I had to call a number in order for them to have someone come to my room to get a replacement for the piece missing. Also, the light up magnifying mirror in the bathroom had finger prints on it again (had the same thing the last time I stayed at the Hyatt).
I chose this particular hotel for a hot tub and did not know it was closed until I got there

column64: ; ; ; ; ; ;My kids prefer this Hyatt for our GBay stays. I watch the price for a week and it stayed relatively high. column250: No one communicated policy on cleaning rooms. We needed to ask for more towels, TP, coffee, etc. It would have been better to just have this in the room because it required multiple trips for us to the front desk, then back. And another trip from a staff member. No one answered the phone at the desk, so that wasn't an option. Way too many parents with unsupervised kids in the pool. At one point on Sat. night, there were over 25 kids in the pool, with more on deck and only 5 adults in the whole area. Kids were NOT well behaved. The staff member in the store Friday night was polite in telling us that you no longer cook pizza in the store and because we were there after 9, out only option was to order out. Ordering a pizza at the Hyatt is something the kids were looking forward to. Closing the seating area early is outright stupid and really has nothing to do with Covid. So many services are recreated with covid as the excuse for lack of service. Yet I paid more for this stay than I have ever before.

2021-04-03 15:39:55] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Dear Ms. Pachapa,

Thank you for sharing your feedback about your experience.

I sincerely apologize for the inconveniences you experienced during your stay. Unfortunately, due to unexpected changed with some reservations for the large dance group at the hotel, it did require a few arrivals to change room types. I know how frustrating that can be. Looking at your account, I do see that Noely, who assisted you at check-in, did reduce your rate by over $40 for that specific room, offered your complimentary parking, and complimentary breakfast for the inconvenience. It is a very rare and always unfortunate occurrence when we have to ask guests to stay in a room that they did not book. Also, because of the late hour of your arrival, coupled with the sold out weekend, our front hotel surface lot was full. We are fortunate to have multiple other lots near the hotel that our guests can utilize. When this happens, we do not charge for parking. 

In regards to the noise levels of the hotel, hours for the restaurant, and hand sanitizer, I have spoke with our Director of Operations and we are continually working to return to normalcy. Our Security Team is working to have more staff on busy weekends and our Housekeeping Team is waiting for more shipments of hand sanitizer. Sadly, across the country, there are still some shortages. As we are still in the middle of a global pandemic, while the hotel was sold out for an event, it still means that our hours are reduced. We are working to bring back our staff, but while your stay we were completely booked, on Sunday, when everyone left, we were left with 23 of our 241 guest rooms occupied. The roller coaster of occupancy we have experienced is frustrating at times and we are doing our best to get back to normal so that we can offer all of our amenities for more hours in the future. I certainly appreciate your understanding as we are working on recovering from the COVID-19 global pandemic.

I hope that once we are fully operational and back to normal, that you will give us another opportunity to impress you. The global pandemic has put a strain on the hospitality industry and affects cities differently. We will get back to normal and I hope that when that happens, you will be able to experience our Midwest hospitality at it's finest.

In addition to the compensation that Noely offered upon check-in, I will also be placing 8000 points in your World of Hyatt account. This is equivalent to one night in our hotel; however, they can be used at any Hyatt Hotels and Resorts anywhere in the world. These points take anywhere from 5-7 business to post into your account. 

If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out - I will be glad to assist you.  

Sincerely,

Paul Zagorski
Front Office Manager
Hyatt Regency Green Bay

Also, because of the late hour of your arrival, coupled with the sold out weekend, our front hotel surface lot was full. We are fortunate to have multiple other lots near the hotel that our guests can utilize. When this happens, we do not charge for parking. 
> 
> In regards to the noise levels of the hotel, hours for the restaurant, and hand sanitizer, I have spoke with our Director of Operations and we are continually working to return to normalcy. Our Security Team is working to have more staff on busy weekends and our Housekeeping Team is waiting for more shipments of hand sanitizer. Sadly, across the country, there are still some shortages. As we are still in the middle of a global pandemic, while the hotel was sold out for an event, it still means that our hours are reduced. We are working to bring back our staff, but while your stay we were completely booked, on Sunday, when everyone left, we were left with 23 of our 241 guest rooms occupied. The roller coaster of occupancy we have experienced is frustrating at times and we are doing our best to get back to normal so that we can offer all of our amenities for more hours in the future. I certainly appreciate your understanding as we are working on recovering from the COVID-19 global pandemic.
> 
> I hope that once we are fully operational and back to normal, that you will give us another opportunity to impress you. The global pandemic has put a strain on the hospitality industry and affects cities differently. We will get back to normal and I hope that when that happens, you will be able to experience our Midwest hospitality at it's finest.
> 
> In addition to the compensation that Noely offered upon check-in, I will also be placing 8000 points in your World of Hyatt account. This is equivalent to one night in our hotel; however, they can be used at any Hyatt Hotels and Resorts anywhere in the world. These points take anywhere from 5-7 business to post into your account.

2021-03-23 14:52:06] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Dear Mr. Quinn,

Thank you for your feedback in our guest survey.

I sincerely apologize for the noisy neighbors your experienced during your stay and the miscommunication about the facemask policy in our hotel. I hope that our Security Team was notified so that they could have an opportunity to speak to neighboring rooms and quiet things down for you. I would like to explain our mask policy as well.

There is a mandate in the State of Wisconsin that facemasks be work inside buildings. Hyatt Hotels have an additional requirement that facemasks/coverings be worn in public areas and if guests choose not to, that we not check the guest in until further information can be gathered. We should have been able to provide a face shield for the guest to be worn. I understand that this was not provided and I apologize for that. If at that time, a guests declines to wear a facemask/covering, we would advise that guests without masks cannot utilize public spaces in the hotel and would be requested to quarantine in their guest room until departure. We do realize that this can be inconvenient. As an asthmatic myself, I have sometimes found masks to be a hindrance in my daily life. However, the policy is in place so that we can do our part to help end the global pandemic and get back to normal. I hope that you understand.

I have spoken with the front desk agent that checked you in so that should we encounter a similar situation, that we can be more tactful and explain the policy more clearly as not to cause frustration. 

Again, I sincerely apologize about the interaction that you had at the front desk. We hope that you and your family remain safe and healthy as we move closer to what we're hoping is the end of the global pandemic. If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out.

Sincerely,

Paul Zagorski
Front Office Manager
Hyatt Regency Green Bay

column250: My daughter left her shower cap at home and needed to take a shower. I contacted the front desk and within 10-minutes two shower caps were delivered to our room door. We appreciate the promptness at such as busy time of the evening.

I didn't mind paying for my Starbucks and granola bar at the front desk, but I didn't like that I could not receive an itemized receipt for reinbursement at my company.  Additionally, I was suprised by how much street noise there was from a 7th floor room.  Otherwise, the rooms were very nice and the staff very pleasant.
We were placed in a room that was adjoined and when we called down to the front desk, they were able to move us to a more private room.  This was very much appreciated.

column250:
I had a very disappointing stay this past weekend. It was a surprise birthday gift for my daughter. She’s never had room service and thinks that would just be the best thing ever. I was wondering if the Hyatt offered that right now, so I called a few days ahead of time to ask about that and the pool. I was told that room service is available on Friday and Saturday nights until 9pm. I was given correct information about pool hours and hot tub being closed. I chose the Hyatt, a more expensive option than other hotels I was considering, specifically for this reason. Paying more money is a sacrifice for us, but I thought it was worth it. When I called the front desk to ask about room service, I was told there was none available. When I said that I had called earlier to ask about this, the front desk staff had no idea what I was talking about. I know it doesn’t sound like a big deal, but I just wanted to do something nice for my daughter after a very difficult year even if it was a financial sacrifice for me to do so. 
A few other notes- our bathroom had hair on the walls, there was a strange white powder under the countertop of the kitchen, and streaming to the tv did not work. I was very disappointed with the way Covid restrictions were handled as well. Even though I did see signs posted, every time I got in the elevator, people would just get on so there were more than four people and numerous groups in the lobby were not wearing masks. I had to go down to the restaurant to order dinner and breakfast. I could not do it from my phone, which made this NOT a “contactless” experience. I would’ve liked to have seen some staff members around to remind people of the rules. As I said, I chose this hotel thinking that we would have room service and would not be exposed to so many people not wearing masks. I wish that I had had the correct information before I made the decision to spend the money to stay at this hotel.

2021-03-12 08:26:04] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Dear Mr. Derkowski,

Thank you for choosing to stay with us and for being a loyal World of Hyatt Globalist. Your honest feedback in our guest survey is greatly appreciated.

I sincerely apologize for the inconveniences you experienced during your stay with us. During the global pandemic, Hyatt Hotels shared a directive to remove anything from the room that was more than one-use or could be touched by multiple guests or colleagues to avoid the spread of COVID-19. At our property, we removed paper products and water bottles. It has helped us be more connected with our guests and has helped us reduce waste by over 60%. While we understand it is an inconvenience to have to request these items, we gladly deliver these items to our guest's rooms. We are trying to do our part to stop the spread of the pandemic and appreciate your understanding. As we slowly return to normal business we hope to add some of the amenities back to the rooms.

In regards to the heating and cooling - you were given correct information. Our property was built in 1989 with a two-pipe system for heating and cooling. This means that in the winter, the entire building is in heat mode and in warmer months, the entire building is in cooling mode. While we are able to control the level of heat with your in-room thermostat, there is not a way to turn on air conditioning. We are hoping that once we are able to return to normal and start our entire hotel renovation that we hoped to have completed by now but delayed due to the global pandemic, that we will have a more modern system to allow our guests to have even more control over their level of comfort. As a native Floridian, I understand how uncomfortable it can be to sleep in a warm room.

As a goodwill gesture for you inconveniences, I am placing 10,000 points on your World of Hyatt Account. This is equivalent to more than one night stay and can be used at any Hyatt in the world. 

I am truly sorry that your stay was not more comfortable. We hope that everyone stays safe and we move past this pandemic sooner rather than later so that travel can be easy and seamless as it once was. If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please to not hesitate to reach out. 

Sincerely,

Paul Zagorski
Front Office Manager
Hyatt Regency Green Bay

column250:
The staff were very friendly and helpful. The main common space of the hotel was clean, tidy and what I would expect from a Hyatt. 

What was disappointing was the condition of the room. While it was clean and prepped for our arrival and stay, the renovation of the room (which it was clear the space must have been recently updated) was poorly done. Like very poorly done. The drywall around fixtures in the wall like the vent and sprinkle system had gaps all around them, the light fixture hanging on the wall was noticeably crooked, the carpet was not laid flat and had bumps throughout the space. The cabinetry was poorly stained and had water damage, as did the drywall in the bathroom next to the shower. Speaking of the shower, the water temperature never got above luke warm. In fact, I’m pretty sure the pool was warmer than the water coming out of the spiget in the shower. 

I have stayed at other Hyatt’s and aesthetically speaking our room missed the mark and did not meet what we had expected to see. 

It was a room that was comfortable to stay in and got the job done at the end of the day, but I expected more attention to detail in the finishes of the room. 

We stayed in 607 if you want to take a gander for yourself.
Employees did a good job of following C-19 restrictions.  This might be challenging in WI due to the fact that the WI Legislature has turned health and safety into a political issue.
I appreciated that each employee we came into contact with had a button of their smiling face.  It was a nice touch to see beyond the mask!

Thank you for staying with us and for sharing your feedback in our guest survey.

I sincerely apologize that the thermostat was not working properly in your room. I have spoken with our Engineers so that they can take a look at it and figure out the problem with it. Unfortunately, we have a two-pipe system in our hotel. Either the entire building is in heat or cooling mode and the thermostat controls the fans in the room. In order to make it cooler, we can turn off the fans from our computer system - that prevents more hot air from coming into the room. We are hoping that in our refurbishment, this will be updated so that if guests wish to have the air conditioning on in the winter, it is possible and will give our guests more control in their room comfort.

In regards to your dining experience, thank you for the compliment! I will ensure that Scott is recognized for his service and managing things on his own. We appreciate you recognizing our staff and definitely look forward to welcoming you back in the future!

2021-01-24 12:13:14] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Dear Ms. Sauer,

Thank you for staying with us and for sharing your feedback in our survey.

I appreciate your thoughtful responses and understand your frustrations. We strive to provide a safe and comfortable environment for all of our guests with amenities that meet our guest's needs. Unfortunately, COVID-19 has forced us to completely revisit our operations and what is available and when. Sadly, our occupancy has been under 30% for most of the last year and with the last minute announcement that fans would be able to go to the Green Bay Packer game against the Los Angeles Rams, we were not prepared for the influx of guests to our property. Had we stayed open, we would have sacrificed service. It appears; however, that was still a misstep on our part. I sincerely apologize that did not have food operations after the game and appreciate your understanding as we are still in the middle of a global pandemic.

As for your additional comments, your weekend was the first weekend we had our hot tub open since March 28th of last year. We tested it to ensure a safe operation and temperature and our Engineering Team has been following up to modify what they need to. I'm sorry that the pool area was so busy. I have spoken to our Head of Security so that we will be better prepared moving forward and have better control over how many guests are in the pool area. We want all of our guests to feel safe at our hotel.

Lastly, we do value your membership in World of Hyatt. For your stay, you earned 5 point per dollar spent. As you earn points, you move your way towards complimentary upgrades and free nights at Hyatt properties around the world. It is disheartening to hear that we did not make you feel valued and I will be working with my staff at the front desk, as well as other managers in the hotel, to modify our interactions to that we do make our guests feel special and part of our family.

My hope is that we are able to move through this pandemic and that your future stays are more streamlined and comfortable. If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out.

Sincerely,

Paul Zagorski
Front Office Manager
Hyatt Regency Green Bay

2021-01-15 11:27:21] Reply Sent: Click here to respond: Dear Dr. Cayce,

Thank you for staying with us and for sharing your feedback in our Guest Survey. We appreciate you being an Explorist with World of Hyatt and your loyalty to the Hyatt family of hotels.

I am glad to hear that your room was comfortable and peaceful. I sincerely apologize though that our policy and procedure for fighting COVID-19 made you uncomfortable. We are currently following State of Wisconsin mandates and Hyatt restrictions regarding the wearing of masks and protocols for cleaning our property. This pandemic has not been good for anyone and we are trying our best to keep our guests and colleagues safe and navigate through all of the new restrictions placed upon everyone. 

Our guest room carpets are cleaned on a regular basis but I would agree it is time for an upgrade. We finished our lobby upgrades in early 2020 and look forward to the next phase in 2021 or early 2022. 

We are constantly working to improve the level of service we provide during these times and I will definitely take this opportunity to tweak how we interact with guests in regards to the pandemic.

If there is anything else you wish to discuss, please do not hesitate to reach out

Sincerely,

Paul Zagorski
